apters. The first treats the growth and shape of medieval literacy itself. Theo other four look afresh at some of the period's major issues--heresy, reform, the Eucharistic controversy, the thought of Anselm, Abelard, and St. Bernard, together with the interpretation of contemporary experience--in the light of literacy's development. The study concludes that written language was the chief integrating instrument for diverse cultural achievements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aLearning and scholarshipxHistoryyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aWritten communicationzEuropexHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBerengar of Tours.  aBoethius.  aByzantium.  aCanonica, Patarene church.  aCatharism.  aChrist, Jesus.  aClement of Rome.  aConstance.  aCorpus Agrimensorum.  aDamian, Peter.  aDonation of Constantine.  aEcclesiastes.  aEdict of Milan.  aEudes of Chartres.  aEusebius.  aGalbert of Bruges.  aGerard of Csanád.  aHenry I of England.  aHeribald of Auxerre.  aHugh of Langres.  aJerusalem.  aJohn of Salisbury.  aLactantius.  aLandulf Senior.  aabstract versus concrete.  aabstraction.  aacculturation.  aallegory.  aantisemitism.  aasceticism.  aauthentication.  abaptism.  abehaviour, symbolic.  aceremony.  acommune.  aconfession.  acovering, allegorical.  acustom.  adecision-making.  aecclesia primitiva.  aempiricism.  aexplanatio.  afascinati.  aformalism.  agrammaticus.  ailliteracy.  aimmram.  aincantation.  airrationality.  ajongleurs.  ajustification.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Gap Yearsz978311078423740uhttps://doi.org/10